2015-06-04 08:45:22	Psi-Jack	leeyaa: Likewise, cp does something mv doesn't, as well.
2015-06-04 08:45:28	alankila	mv in the optimal case can simply reattach the inode (e.g. file data) to a different place in tree
2015-06-04 08:45:59	alankila	so its performance can be independent of the file size being moved
2015-06-04 08:46:11	leeyaa	Psi-Jack: ok so if i use mv and cp for performance tests i should consider them as two different tests ?
2015-06-04 08:46:12	alankila	not *will be* because mv can only be done within the same filesystem quickly
2015-06-04 08:46:24	peetaur2	leeyaa: if you mv a file to another dir on the SAME filesystem, it only has to modify the dir, not the file; if you move to another fs, then it copies the file like cp would, then removes the old
